  <div class="container">
    <div class="article-page__body">
      <div class="article-page__content rte">
        <p>Every outerwear silhouette trades off warmth, weight, and versatility differently. Here's how the four most common styles actually compare, so you can match the jacket to your climate and how you'll wear it rather than just the look.</p>

        <h2>Bomber jacket</h2>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> mild-to-cool weather, everyday styling.</p>
        <p>Cropped, ribbed cuffs and hem, typically light-to-mid weight. Bombers layer easily over hoodies or sweaters but offer the least wind and rain protection of the four styles — treat it as a mid-warmth piece you layer under in real cold, not a stand-alone winter coat.</p>

        <h2>Parka</h2>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> sustained cold, wind, and snow.</p>
        <p>Long length (usually to the thigh or knee), often with a fur-lined or faux-fur hood and a warm liner. Parkas are built for exposure — waiting for transit, walking in snow, standing outside for long stretches. The tradeoff is bulk and less flexibility for layering underneath dressier outfits.</p>

        <h2>Puffer jacket</h2>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> maximum warmth-to-weight, active use.</p>
        <p>Quilted baffles filled with down or synthetic insulation trap the most warmth per ounce of any style here. Great for commuting, travel, or anywhere you need serious warmth without serious weight — packable puffers are also easy to stuff into a bag when you don't need them.</p>

        <h2>Wool or shearling coat</h2>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> smart-casual and business settings.</p>
        <p>Wool blends and shearling-lined coats read more "dressed up" than technical outerwear and pair naturally with tailored clothing. They're warm in dry cold but generally less wind- and water-resistant than a technical shell, so they suit city wear more than exposed, wet conditions.</p>

